---
import Callout from '../../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import Code from '../../../../../components/Code.astro';
import ReplyTask from '../../../../../components/ReplyTask.astro';
import SessionPage from '../../../../../components/SessionPage.astro';
import SessionSection from '../../../../../components/SessionSection.astro';

const propertyChoices = `// Choice 1
public string Status { get; set; }

// Choice 2
public string Status { get; private set; }`;

const transitionCode = `// Initial value: Status == "Pending"
public bool Confirm()
{
    if (Status != "Pending") return false;

    Status = "Confirmed";
    return true;
}`;

const replyText = `[learn:csharp/006:q1]

Use only the supplied facts, choices, and method. Do not write code. Reply with four short answers.

Domain facts:
- TableBookingRequest has Name and PartySize. It is one request value supplied as a whole; this workflow does not change it.
- TableBooking represents the same continuing booking. Its Status may change only through Confirm().

Available type choices for each: positional record or class.

Status property choices:
1. public string Status { get; set; }
2. public string Status { get; private set; }

Supplied transition method:
// Initial value: Status == "Pending"
public bool Confirm()
{
    if (Status != "Pending") return false;

    Status = "Confirmed";
    return true;
}

A. For TableBookingRequest, choose positional record or class and give one short reason.
Answer:

B. For TableBooking, choose positional record or class and give one short reason.
Answer:

C. Which Status property is safer for this design: choice 1 or choice 2? Why?
Answer:

D. On one new TableBooking, call Confirm() twice in sequence. Predict both calls:
- First Confirm(): returned Boolean / final Status
- Second Confirm(): returned Boolean / final Status
Answer:`;
---

<SessionPage
  title="Session 6 · C#: public surface choice"
  heading="Choose what callers may change, then trace the guard"
  lede="Make one fresh record/class choice, select the safer public property surface, and predict two calls to a supplied state-transition method."
  backHref="/topics/csharp/"
  backLabel="C# sessions"
>
  <SessionSection title="A compact reference for the decision">
    <ul>
      <li>A positional <code>record</code> is a compact option for a value-shaped description supplied as one whole. It also has compiler-supported value equality.</li>
      <li>A <code>class</code> is a natural option for one continuing domain object with a guarded lifecycle.</li>
      <li>Neither keyword decides mutability by itself: a record is not automatically immutable, and a class is not automatically mutable.</li>
      <li><code>get; private set;</code> lets outside callers read a property while reserving assignment for code inside the declaring type.</li>
    </ul>
    <Callout>
      Decide from the facts of this design. Then trace the method from top to bottom separately for each call; the second call starts from the status left by the first.
    </Callout>
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Fresh domain facts and candidate surfaces">
    <p><code>TableBookingRequest</code> contains <code>Name</code> and <code>PartySize</code>. It is supplied as one request value, and this workflow does not change it.</p>
    <p><code>TableBooking</code> represents the same continuing booking. Its <code>Status</code> may change only through <code>Confirm()</code>.</p>
    <p>For each type, your available choices are <strong>positional record</strong> or <strong>class</strong>.</p>
    <Code code={propertyChoices} lang="csharp" />
  </SessionSection>

  <SessionSection title="Supplied transition method">
    <Code code={transitionCode} lang="csharp" />
    <p>The initial status and every branch needed for the prediction are shown. Treat the two calls as sequential calls on the same booking.</p>
  </SessionSection>

  <ReplyTask id="learn:csharp/006:q1" difficulty={3}>
    <p><strong>Phone-ready:</strong> use only the supplied facts, choices, and method; write no code; give four short answers.</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Choose <strong>positional record</strong> or <strong>class</strong> for <code>TableBookingRequest</code>, with one short reason.</li>
      <li>Choose <strong>positional record</strong> or <strong>class</strong> for <code>TableBooking</code>, with one short reason.</li>
      <li>Choose the safer <code>Status</code> property surface, and say why.</li>
      <li>On one new booking, call <code>Confirm()</code> twice in sequence. For each call, predict the returned Boolean and final status.</li>
    </ol>
  </ReplyTask>
</SessionPage>
